This page gives you guidance on how to stay safely in Romania as a visitor, if you are unable to return to the UK.
Everyone should comply with the measures put in place in Romania to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
Moving around in Romania
For information on entering Romania, see Entry Requirements.
Romania moved from a State of Emergency to a State of Alert on 15 May. Lockdown is being eased gradually and there remain many specific measures:
Movement out of doors is allowed but there remain restrictions on moving between different towns, cities, and counties. Parks will reopen.
Gatherings of groups of more than three are not allowed.
Wearing protective masks or face coverings is now mandatory on public transport, workplaces, and in enclosed public spaces.
Temperature checks are in operation at many institutions that work with the public.
Hotels have been allowed to open, but only when observing a specific set of rules. Restaurants remain closed.
Food retailers, opticians, dental practices, and beauty salons are allowed to reopen. Large malls remain closed. Churches may perform services outdoors.
Schools and universities remain closed, but schools may reopen from 2 June for students in exam years.
Travel between towns, cities, and counties in Romania remains restricted, with movement allowed for the following reasons:
Agricultural activities
Work-related travel
Taking care of properties, children, or relatives
Medical treatment
Death of a family member
There is new version of the Romanian movement declaration form which you will need to fill in and carry when moving between towns, cities, and counties.
Health
